org.eclipse.jface.window.IShellProvider
public class NewProblemDialog
extends org.eclipse.jface.dialogs.ErrorDialog

The ProblemDialog is the graphical front-end for the g-Eclipse problem reporting mechanism. It essentially behaves like the Eclipse ErrorDialog but offers the user solutions that come with a specified problem. Nevertheless the ProblemDialog may also be used with ordinary CoreExceptions, so it may completely replace the ErrorDialog.

openProblem

public static int openProblem(org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Shell parent,
                              java.lang.String dialogTitle,
                              java.lang.String message,
                              java.lang.Throwable throwable)
Static helper method to open a ProblemDialog.

Parameters:
parent - The dialog's parent Shell.
dialogTitle - The title of the dialog.
message - The message that will be primarily displayed to the user.
throwable - Any type of exception to be shown to the user. If this is a GridException the associated IProblem will be used to build up the dialog. If this is a CoreException the associated IStatus will be used to build up the dialog.
Returns:
The return code of the dialog. This may be one of the ErrorDialog's standard return codes or SOLVE if the dialog was closed with the action of a solution.

openProblem

public static int openProblem(org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Shell parent,
                              java.lang.String dialogTitle,
                              java.lang.String message,
                              GridException gExc,
                              SolutionRegistry solutionRegistry)
Static helper method to open a ProblemDialog.

Parameters:
parent - The dialog's parent Shell.
dialogTitle - The title of the dialog.
message - The message that will be primarily displayed to the user.
gExc - A GridException that will be used to build up the dialog.
solutionRegistry - The SolutionRegistry that is used to map solution IDs to solutions. If this is null the UISolutionRegistry is taken as default.
Returns:
The return code of the dialog. This may be one of the ErrorDialog's standard return codes or SOLVE if the dialog was closed with the action of a solution.
